                <head>28. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>
                    and Secretary of State Cyrus <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1">Vance</persName> met
                    May 18–20, 1977, in Geneva to discuss <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> II
                    and the Middle East. Four of the five meetings addressed <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> and especially how the United States and
                    Union of Soviet Socialist Republics could reach an agreement despite differing
                    goals and objectives following the Vladivostok negotiations. For a summary of
                    those meetings, see <ref target="frus1969-76v33#d167">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume XXXIII, <gloss
                            target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> II, 1972–1980, Document 167</ref>.</p>
            </div>
